Contributing to the iChild RAG Application

Thank you for considering contributing to the iChild RAG project! We appreciate all contributions, whether it’s reporting issues, suggesting improvements, or submitting pull requests. By contributing, you help make the project better and more useful for everyone.

How to Contribute

1. Fork the Repository

	•	If you haven’t already, fork the repository to your own GitHub account by clicking the “Fork” button in the top right corner of this page.

2. Clone the Repository

	•	Clone your forked repository to your local machine using the following command:

`git clone https://github.com/<your-username>/iChild-RAG.git`

3. Create a New Branch

	•	Create a new branch for the feature or fix you are working on:

`git checkout -b <branch-name>`

	•	It’s important to keep your changes organized and isolated in separate branches for each task/functionality.

4. Make Changes

	•	Work on your changes in the new branch. Be sure to write clear, concise commit messages.
	•	Follow the project’s coding standards and ensure your changes are consistent with the existing code style.

5. Test Your Changes

	•	Test your changes thoroughly to ensure they do not break existing functionality.
	•	If applicable, add unit tests for new features or bug fixes to maintain the integrity of the codebase.

6. Commit Changes

	•	Commit your changes with clear and descriptive commit messages. Each commit should represent a single logical change.

`git commit -m "Describe the change made"`

7. Push to Your Fork

	•	Push your changes to your fork on GitHub:

`git push origin <branch-name>`

8. Create a Pull Request

	•	Go to the original repository and create a pull request (PR) from your fork’s branch.
	•	Include a clear description of the changes you’ve made in the PR. If the PR is related to a specific issue, reference it by including the issue number, e.g., Fixes #123.

Code Style

	•	Formatting: Follow consistent indentation and code formatting as seen in the project. For Python code, use PEP 8 guidelines.
	•	Naming Conventions: Use descriptive and meaningful names for functions, variables, and classes.
	•	Docstrings: Include docstrings for all functions, classes, and methods to explain their purpose and usage.

Reporting Issues

If you encounter a bug or have an idea for an improvement, please open an issue in the repository. When reporting an issue, please include:
	•	A clear description of the problem or feature request.
	•	Steps to reproduce the issue (if applicable).
	•	Expected and actual behavior.
	•	Screenshots, error messages, or log files, if relevant.

Testing

We aim for a codebase that is well-tested. If your contribution affects functionality, please ensure that your changes include:
	•	Unit tests for new features or bug fixes.
	•	Ensure existing tests continue to pass after your changes.

License

By contributing to this project, you agree that your contributions will be licensed under the same open-source license as the repository TAMU.

Acknowledgments

We would like to thank all contributors for helping improve the iChild RAG application!

